            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Ling Lam\u2019s understanding of the world was forged in the organized chaos of her parents\u2019 corner grocery store in San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District. The only child of immigrants from Hong Kong, she spent her youth stocking shelves and managing inventory, developing an intuitive grasp of logistics long before she knew the term. While her parents worked grueling hours, their dream was for Mei-Ling to have a life of the mind, not of manual labor. She honored their sacrifice, becoming the first in her family to attend college, earning a business degree from UC Berkeley.\n\nHer early career was a steady, methodical climb. She found her calling not in abstract finance, but in the tangible world of how things are made and moved. This led her to a specialized Master's in Supply Chain Management. Her professional life clicked into place; she was brilliant at optimizing complex systems and untangling operational knots. However, her singular focus on her career created friction in her personal life, culminating in a difficult divorce at 38. This turning point forced a painful but necessary recalibration.\n\nNow, at 43, Mei-Ling has crafted a life of deliberate balance. She sold the suburban house she shared with her ex-husband and moved into a sleek apartment in Hayes Valley. Her daily routine is a testament to the efficiency she champions at work. An early morning yoga class is followed by a walk to a local cafe for an oat milk latte before she catches a Muni bus for the 3.8-mile commute to the manufacturing firm in SoMa where she is the Director of Operations.\n\nHer social life is small but meaningful, centered around a few close friends who appreciate her dry wit and unwavering loyalty. She remains devoted to her aging parents, visiting them every Sunday. Though professionally successful, Mei-Ling dreams of a new chapter. Her ultimate aspiration is to launch her own consulting firm, advising small, family-run businesses\u2014the kind her parents owned\u2014on how to modernize and thrive. She wants to bring her corporate expertise back to the community that raised her, ensuring their legacies are as efficient and enduring as the systems she now commands."
